<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="577" type="tl">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">TL.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
The type locality was originally stated as 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘Australia’">'Australia'</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Sowerby, GB II" journalOrPublisher="Sowerby, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" publicationUrl="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8209501" refId="B121" refString="Sowerby, GB II, 1872. Monograph of the genus Limnaea. In: Reeve L. Conchologia Iconica. L. Reeve and Co, London, 18, no pagination, plates 1-15. https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8209501" title="Monograph of the genus Limnaea. In: Reeve L. Conchologia Iconica. L. Reeve and Co, London, 18, no pagination, plates 1 - 15." url="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8209501" year="1872">Sowerby 1872</bibRefCitation>
). It is, however, erroneous. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.96210" author="Hanley, S" journalOrPublisher="Reeve and Co, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" refId="B48" refString="Hanley, S, Theobald, W, 1876. Conchologia Indica: Illustrations of the Land and Freshwater Shells of British India. L. Reeve and Co, London, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.96210" title="Conchologia Indica: Illustrations of the Land and Freshwater Shells of British India. L." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.96210" year="1876">Hanley and Theobald (1876)</bibRefCitation>
gave the proper type locality: Kashmir.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="577" type="types">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">Types.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">NHMUK. The syntypes were inspected by us.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits Northern India (Kashmir), Nepal, China (Western Tibet and Himalaya Range) and, probably, Tajikistan (Pamir Mts.) [
<bibRefCitation author="Subba Rao, MV" journalOrPublisher="Zoological Survey of India, Calcutta" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" refId="B126" refString="Subba Rao, MV, 1989. Handbook: Freshwater Molluscs of India. Zoological Survey of India, Calcutta" title="Handbook: Freshwater Molluscs of India." year="1989">Subba Rao 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 156" refId="B43" refString="Gloeer, P, Boessneck, U, 2013. Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 142: 137 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" title="Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" volume="142" year="2013">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bössneck">Boessneck</normalizedToken>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" author="Aksenova, OV" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Reports" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="1 - 17" refId="B1" refString="Aksenova, OV, Bolotov, IN, Gofarov, MY, Kondakov, AV, Vinarski, MV, Bespalaya, YV, Kolosova, YS, Palatov, DM, Sokolova, SE, Spitsyn, VM, Tomilova, AA, Travina, OV, Vikhrev, IV, 2018a. Species richness, molecular taxonomy and biogeography of the radicine pond snails (Gastropoda: Lymnaeidae) in the Old World. Scientific Reports 8 (11199): 1 - 17, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" title="Species richness, molecular taxonomy and biogeography of the radicine pond snails (Gastropoda: Lymnaeidae) in the Old World." url="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" volume="8" year="2018 a">Aksenova et al. 2018a</bibRefCitation>
]. The record of this species from Tajikistan is based on numerous shells from ZISP collection (see Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Shells of species in the genus Radix. A. Radix auricularia (28.08.2013, Kazakhstan, Karaganda Region, Suresai River; LMBI); B. R. alticola (20.06.2012, Tajikistan, a hot spring near Djelandy village; LMBI); C. R. alticola (01.07.2016, Tajikistan, a warm brook near Dzhaushangoz village; LMBI); D. R. brevicauda (Kashmir, a syntype; NHMUK); E. R. brevicauda (05.08.1948, Tajikistan, Pamir Mts., Shaimak village, in a warm spring; ZISP); F. R. euphratica (26.06.2016, Tajikistan, Dushanbe, a fountain near the President's palace; LMBI); G. R. euphratica (04.07.2016, Tajikistan, a roadside ditch near Kurban-Shakhid village; LMBI); H. R. euphratica (without date, Iraq, Bagdad; NHMUK); I. R. makhrovi, the holotype (China, Tibet, a roadside ditch west of the Lhasa River mouth; ZISP); J. R. plicatula, a probable syntype (China, Chusan, NHMUK); K. R. plicatula (26.07.2017, China, Uyghuria, Bagrash-kol' Lake; LMBI); L. R. plicatula (26.11.2014, China, Bejing, an artificial pond in the former Emperor's summer palace; LMBI). Scale bars: 2 mm (B-C, F-L), 5 mm (A, D-E, K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.52860.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448267" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">3E</figureCitation>
), virtually identical with the syntypes of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species has not been registered from the ex-USSR territory (
<bibRefCitation author="Vinarski, MV" journalOrPublisher="Severtsov Institute of Ecology and Evolution of RAS, Moscow" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" refId="B142" refString="Vinarski, MV, Kantor, YI, 2016. Analytical catalogue of fresh and brackish water molluscs of Russia and adjacent countries. A.N. Severtsov Institute of Ecology and Evolution of RAS, Moscow" title="Analytical catalogue of fresh and brackish water molluscs of Russia and adjacent countries. A. N." year="2016">Vinarski and Kantor 2016</bibRefCitation>
) and hereby we, for the first time, include it in the malacofauna of the former Soviet Union. However, this record is still not corroborated genetically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
The shell of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is ear-shaped, with low spire and greatly expanded aperture. Generally, in many ways, it resembles the shell of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 156" refId="B43" refString="Gloeer, P, Boessneck, U, 2013. Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 142: 137 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" title="Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" volume="142" year="2013">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bössneck">Boessneck</normalizedToken>
(2013
</bibRefCitation>
: 153) note that there are no substantial differences between the two species, which are probable synonyms. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Annandale, N" journalOrPublisher="Records of the Indian Museum" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 189" publicationUrl="http://faunaofindia.nic.in/PDFVolumes/records/027/03/0137-0189.pdf" refId="B13" refString="Annandale, N, Rao, HS, 1925. Materials for a revision of the recent Indian Limnaeidae (Mollusca Pulmonata). Records of the Indian Museum 27: 137 - 189, http://faunaofindia.nic.in/PDFVolumes/records/027/03/0137-0189.pdf" title="Materials for a revision of the recent Indian Limnaeidae (Mollusca Pulmonata)." url="http://faunaofindia.nic.in/PDFVolumes/records/027/03/0137-0189.pdf" volume="27" year="1925">Annandale and Rao (1925)</bibRefCitation>
reported the structure of the jaw and radula of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct from that of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The anatomical structure of the discussed species, described and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 156" refId="B43" refString="Gloeer, P, Boessneck, U, 2013. Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 142: 137 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" title="Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" volume="142" year="2013">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bössneck">Boessneck</normalizedToken>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
, is typical for the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Lymnaeidae" genus="Radix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Radix" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">Radix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Our molecular analysis recovered 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species sister to 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" author="Aksenova, OV" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Reports" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="1 - 17" refId="B1" refString="Aksenova, OV, Bolotov, IN, Gofarov, MY, Kondakov, AV, Vinarski, MV, Bespalaya, YV, Kolosova, YS, Palatov, DM, Sokolova, SE, Spitsyn, VM, Tomilova, AA, Travina, OV, Vikhrev, IV, 2018a. Species richness, molecular taxonomy and biogeography of the radicine pond snails (Gastropoda: Lymnaeidae) in the Old World. Scientific Reports 8 (11199): 1 - 17, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" title="Species richness, molecular taxonomy and biogeography of the radicine pond snails (Gastropoda: Lymnaeidae) in the Old World." url="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-018-29451-1" volume="8" year="2018 a">Aksenova et al. 2018a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
We may indicate some conchological differences between 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter species is of smaller size, the largest syntype shell is 18.1 mm (our data) and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" pagination="137 - 156" refId="B43" refString="Gloeer, P, Boessneck, U, 2013. Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species. Archiv fuer Molluskenkunde 142: 137 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" title="Freshwater molluscs from Nepal and North India with the description of seven new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/arch.moll/1869-0963/142/137-156" volume="142" year="2013">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bössneck">Boessneck</normalizedToken>
(2013)
</bibRefCitation>
mention that 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may reach 20 mm in height. Next, the columellar depression in shells of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very prominent, whereas, in 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is typically weakly developed (compare Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. The scheme of measurements of the shell (A) and the parts of the copulatory apparatus (B). Abbreviations: SH - shell height; SW - shell width; SpH - spire height; BWH - body whorl height; AH - aperture height; AW - aperture width; PP - length of praeputium; PS - penis sheath length. A - after Vinarski (2016 b)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.52860.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448266" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">2A</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. The scheme of measurements of the shell (A) and the parts of the copulatory apparatus (B). Abbreviations: SH - shell height; SW - shell width; SpH - spire height; BWH - body whorl height; AH - aperture height; AW - aperture width; PP - length of praeputium; PS - penis sheath length. A - after Vinarski (2016 b)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.52860.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448266" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">2D, E</figureCitation>
). Lastly, the spire whorls in 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually flattened, while in 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these are visibly convex and rounded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="577" type="nomenclature remark">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">Nomenclature remark.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="577">
The name 
<taxonomicName authority="Blainville, 1824" authorityName="G.B.Sowerby II" authorityYear="1872" class="Gastropoda" family="Lymnaeidae" genus="Limnaea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Limnaea brevicauda" order="Hygrophila" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">Limnaea brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sowerby is the oldest available one to designate a lymnaeid species, sister to 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, restricted in its distribution to the Central Asia mountain regions. The taxonomic identity of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. brevicauda" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="brevicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. brevicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as well its close affinity to 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. auricularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="577" rank="species" species="auricularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="577">R. auricularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was confirmed by the inspection of the extant syntypes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
